  "brief": {
    "sheet_title": "Full I/O wiring diagram (page 2-38) for the DURApulse GS20 / GS20X variable-frequency drive — the complete power and control terminal hookup.",
    "purpose": "This drawing shows how to wire an AC drive (VFD) that runs a three-phase motor. Incoming one- or three-phase power passes through a circuit breaker/fuse and a main contactor (MC) into the drive input terminals R/L1, S/L2, T/L3, and the drive puts out variable-frequency three-phase power on U/T1, V/T2, W/T3 to the motor. An internal DC bus (DC-, DC+/+1, +2/B1, B2) can take an optional DC reactor and an optional brake resistor. On the control side the drive supplies +24 V for digital inputs DI1–DI7 (defaults: DI1=Forward/Stop, DI2=Reverse/Stop, DI3–DI6=multi-step speeds, DI7 spare/33 kHz pulse), all returning to the digital common DCM, wired NPN/sink by default. A 5 kΩ potentiometer across +10 V / AI1 / ACM (or a 0-10 V / 4-20 mA signal on AI2) sets the speed reference. Outputs include a form-C multi-function relay (R1O/R1C/R1), transistor/photocoupler outputs DO/DO1/DO2 with common DOC, an analog output AO1 (0-10 V or 0/4-20 mA), a Modbus RS-485 port, and a Safe-Torque-Off (STO1/STO2) circuit driven from a Safety PLC/E-STOP.",
