    "troubleshooting_example": "Motor won't start on a Forward command: with the drive powered, meter DI1/FWD to DCM while the FWD contact is closed — you should see the drive's ~24 V input voltage collapse/appear per the sink wiring. Then meter the same contact directly at the +24 V and DI1/FWD terminals: if +24 V is present and the closed field contact does NOT pull DI1/FWD to DCM, the fault is in the external switch/wiring; if DI1/FWD does toggle correctly at the drive terminal but the drive still won't run, the fault is inside the drive (or an interlock such as STO). Note: this sheet does NOT show the drive's internal run logic or parameter settings, so confirm the run source and STO status separately — an open STO1/STO2 (E-STOP / Safety PLC) will also inhibit running regardless of the run command.",
    "safety_context": "This is a drive with high-energy circuits. The AC input is one- or three-phase mains and the DC bus retains a lethal charge after power-off — the sheet does not print the exact line/bus voltage, so treat it as unknown-but-dangerous and verify with the drive's rating label. For any continuity/resistance checks on motor leads, DC-bus, or brake resistor, de-energize, lock out, and confirm the DC bus has discharged to a safe level with a meter before touching. Control terminals carry the printed low levels (+24 VDC control, +10 VDC reference, DO 30 VDC, DO1/DO2 48 VDC, relay up to 250 VAC/30 VDC) — the relay contact can carry up to 250 VAC even when the drive appears 'off', so treat R1O/R1C/R1 as potentially live. STO is a safety function; do not defeat the STO wiring or reinsert the factory jumper as a workaround.",
